Here is the full performance analysis:

---

## Scan Execution Checklist

| Recipe | Hits |
|--------|------|
| `.IndexOf(string)` w/o StringComparison | 0 ✅ |
| `.Substring(` | 0 ✅ |
| `.StartsWith/.EndsWith` w/o StringComparison | 0 ✅ |
| `.ToLower()/.ToUpper()` | 0 (but 1× `.ToLowerInvariant()`) |
| `params` | **2** |
| Chained `.Replace(` | 0 ✅ |
| LINQ operators (`.Select/.Where/.Take/.Aggregate`) | **16** |
| `.Any/.All` | **1** |
| `.ToList()` | **1** |
| `.ToArray()` | **3** |
| `new List<` (in method bodies) | **1** |
| Unsealed non-abstract non-static classes | **1** (0 sealed) |
| `Enum.ToString()` | **1** |
| `.Trim()` | **1** |
| `string.Format` | 0 ✅ |
| `$"` interpolation | 3 ✅ |

---

## Findings

### 1. 🔴 LINQ Chains on Hot Path (16 instances)

**Impact:** Every `Humanize` call allocates 3-6 enumerators, 2-4 delegates, and intermediate lists/arrays. At millions of calls/minute, this is the dominant source of GC pressure.

**Files:** `TimeSpanFormatting.cs:L128, L140, L143, L146, L149, L158, L169, L244, L261-262, L270-272, L284, L304`

**Fix:** Replace LINQ chains with `foreach` loops. Example for the worst compound site (`SetPrecisionOfTimeSpan` + `ConcatenateTimeSpanParts`):

```csharp
// SetPrecisionOfTimeSpan — replace 3 LINQ operators + list materialization
private static List<string?> SetPrecisionOfTimeSpan(
    List<string?> timeParts, int precision, bool countEmptyUnits)
{
    var result = new List<string?>(precision);
    int count = 0;
    foreach (var part in timeParts)
    {
        if (count >= precision) break;
        if (countEmptyUnits) count++;
        if (part != null)
        {
            if (!countEmptyUnits) count++;
            result.Add(part);
        }
    }
    return result;
}

// IsContainingOnlyNullValue — replace .Any() with loop
private static bool IsContainingOnlyNullValue(List<string?> timeParts)
{
    foreach (var part in timeParts)
        if (part != null) return false;
    return true;
}

// ConcatenateTimeSpanParts — replace .Where().ToList() + .Take()
private static string ConcatenateTimeSpanParts(
    List<string?> timeSpanParts, CultureInfo culture, string collectionSeparator)
{
    int nonNullCount = 0;
    foreach (var p in timeSpanParts)
        if (p != null) nonNullCount++;

    if (nonNullCount == 0) return "no time";
    if (nonNullCount == 1)
    {
        foreach (var p in timeSpanParts)
            if (p != null) return p;
    }

    var sb = new StringBuilder();
    int index = 0;
    foreach (var p in timeSpanParts)
    {
        if (p == null) continue;
        index++;
        if (index == nonNullCount)
        {
            sb.Append(" and ").Append(p);
        }
        else
        {
            if (index > 1) sb.Append(collectionSeparator);
            sb.Append(p);
        }
    }
    return sb.ToString();
}
```

Similarly in `HumanizeDisplayStrings`: replace the `.Select().Where().ToArray()` chain (L270-272) with a `foreach` that trims and filters in one pass.

---

### 2. 🔴 Enum.ToString() + ToLowerInvariant() per Time Unit (1 site, called N× per Humanize)

**Impact:** `FormatTimePart` (L175) does `unit.ToString().ToLowerInvariant()` — reflection-based enum name + a second allocation. Called for every non-zero time unit, every log entry. At millions/min this is 2-8M+ allocations/min.

**Files:** `TimeSpanFormatting.cs:L175`

**Fix:** Replace with a cached lookup:

```csharp
private static string GetUnitName(TimeUnit unit) => unit switch
{
    TimeUnit.Year => "year",
    TimeUnit.Month => "month",
    TimeUnit.Week => "week",
    TimeUnit.Day => "day",
    TimeUnit.Hour => "hour",
    TimeUnit.Minute => "minute",
    TimeUnit.Second => "second",
    TimeUnit.Millisecond => "millisecond",
    _ => unit.ToString().ToLowerInvariant()
};
```

---

### 3. 🟡 `params IStringTransformer[]` Without 1-Arg Overload (2 instances)

**Impact:** Allocates a `T[]` on every call. The common 1-transformer case pays an array allocation needlessly.

**Files:** `TimeSpanFormatting.cs:L303`

**Fix:** Add a 1-argument overload:

```csharp
public static string Transform(
    this string input, CultureInfo culture, IStringTransformer transformer) =>
    transformer.Transform(input);
```

**Caveat:** On .NET 9+ / C# 13, consider changing to `params ReadOnlySpan<IStringTransformer>` instead.

---

### 4. 🟡 Double `.Select()` Chain in Object Formatter Overload (1 site)

**Impact:** L261-262 chains two `.Select()` calls (2 enumerators + 2 delegates). Easily merged into one.

**Files:** `TimeSpanFormatting.cs:L259-262`

**Fix:** Merge into a single `.Select()`:

```csharp
return HumanizeDisplayStrings(
    collection.Select(item => objectFormatter(item)?.ToString()),
    separator);
```

---

### 5. 🟡 Redundant Allocation in Zero-Time Path (1 site)

**Impact:** L76 creates a `List<string?>` via `CreateTimePartsWithNoTimeValue("no time")` only to index `[0]` and null-coalesce to the same string. Two unnecessary allocations on the zero-time path.

**Files:** `TimeSpanFormatting.cs:L76`

**Fix:** Return `"no time"` directly.

---

### 6. 🟡 Unsealed Class with Virtual Methods (1 of 1 class unsealed)

**Impact:** `DefaultCollectionFormatter` has 4 `virtual` methods and is not subclassed in this file. Sealing enables JIT devirtualization.

**Files:** `TimeSpanFormatting.cs:L208`

**Fix:** Add `sealed` — `public sealed class DefaultCollectionFormatter`. If subclassing is intended by consumers, leave as-is.

---

### 7. ℹ️ Static Init Uses LINQ (1 site)

**Impact:** L41 uses `Enumerable.Reverse(Enum.GetValues<TimeUnit>())` — allocates at startup, not per-call.

**Files:** `TimeSpanFormatting.cs:L41`

**Fix:** Replace with a literal array:

```csharp
private static readonly TimeUnit[] TimeUnits =
    [TimeUnit.Millisecond, TimeUnit.Second, TimeUnit.Minute,
     TimeUnit.Hour, TimeUnit.Day, TimeUnit.Week, TimeUnit.Month, TimeUnit.Year];
```

---

### Positive Findings

- ✅ No `string.Format` boxing — interpolation used throughout
- ✅ No `.Substring()` allocations
- ✅ No missing `StringComparison` on `IndexOf`/`StartsWith`/`EndsWith`/`Contains`
- ✅ No `HttpClient`, `Regex`, or serialization issues
- ✅ `List<string?>` pre-sized with capacity 8 at L91

---

## Summary

| Severity | Count | Top Issue |
|----------|-------|-----------|
| 🔴 Critical | 2 | LINQ chains allocating 3-6 enumerators + delegates per call; `Enum.ToString()` on every time unit |
| 🟡 Moderate | 4 | `params` array, double `.Select()`, redundant zero-time alloc, unsealed class |
| ℹ️ Info | 1 | Static-init LINQ (one-time cost) |

> ⚠️ **Disclaimer:** These results are generated by an AI assistant and are non-deterministic. Findings may include false positives, miss real issues, or suggest changes that are incorrect for your specific context. Always verify recommendations with benchmarks and human review before applying changes to production code.
